## Add Dark Mode with next-themes

### 1. Install next-themes
- Run: `npm install next-themes`.
- next-themes is a zero-dependency library that manages theme state via a React context and persists the choice in `localStorage`.
- If you are using pnpm or yarn, use the equivalent command.

### 2. Configure Tailwind CSS for dark mode
- Open `tailwind.config.ts` (or `tailwind.config.js`).
- Set `darkMode: 'class'` so Tailwind applies dark variants when the `dark` class is on `<html>`:
  ```ts
  // tailwind.config.ts
  import type { Config } from 'tailwindcss';
  const config: Config = {
    darkMode: 'class',
    content: ['./src/**/*.{ts,tsx}'],
    theme: { extend: {} },
    plugins: [],
  };
  export default config;
  ```
- If you are on **Tailwind CSS v4** (CSS-first config), add this to your global CSS file instead:
  ```css
  @import 'tailwindcss';
  @variant dark (&:where(.dark, .dark *));
  ```
- Do NOT use `darkMode: 'media'` — it prevents the user from manually toggling the theme.

### 3. Wrap the root layout in ThemeProvider
- Open `src/app/layout.tsx` (App Router).
- Import and wrap children with `ThemeProvider`:
  ```tsx
  import { ThemeProvider } from 'next-themes';

  export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
    return (
      <html lang="en" suppressHydrationWarning>
        <body>
          <ThemeProvider
            attribute="class"
            defaultTheme="system"
            enableSystem
            disableTransitionOnChange
          >
            {children}
          </ThemeProvider>
        </body>
      </html>
    );
  }
  ```
- **`attribute="class"`** — next-themes adds/removes the `dark` class on `<html>`, matching your Tailwind config.
- **`suppressHydrationWarning`** on `<html>` — next-themes changes the `class` attribute during hydration; without this React will log a mismatch warning.
- **`disableTransitionOnChange`** — prevents a flash of unstyled content (FOUC) during theme switch.
- `ThemeProvider` is a Client Component; the layout file itself can remain a Server Component because React handles this transparently.

### 4. Build a theme toggle component
- Create `src/components/theme-toggle.tsx`:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { useTheme } from 'next-themes';
  import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

  export function ThemeToggle() {
    const { theme, setTheme } = useTheme();
    const [mounted, setMounted] = useState(false);

    useEffect(() => { setMounted(true); }, []);

    if (!mounted) return null;

    return (
      <button
        onClick={() => setTheme(theme === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark')}
        aria-label="Toggle theme"
      >
        {theme === 'dark' ? '☀️ Light' : '🌙 Dark'}
      </button>
    );
  }
  ```
- **The `mounted` guard is mandatory.** `useTheme()` returns `undefined` on the server and during the first render to prevent hydration mismatches. Rendering nothing until mounted avoids this.
- This component must be a Client Component (`'use client'`) because it uses `useTheme` which is a React hook.

### 5. (Optional) System theme selector — three-way toggle
- Extend the toggle to support `system`, `light`, and `dark`:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { useTheme } from 'next-themes';
  import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';

  const themes = ['system', 'light', 'dark'] as const;

  export function ThemeSelector() {
    const { theme, setTheme } = useTheme();
    const [mounted, setMounted] = useState(false);
    useEffect(() => { setMounted(true); }, []);
    if (!mounted) return null;
    return (
      <select value={theme} onChange={e => setTheme(e.target.value)}>
        {themes.map(t => <option key={t} value={t}>{t}</option>)}
      </select>
    );
  }
  ```

### 6. (Optional) shadcn/ui integration
- If you are using shadcn/ui, it ships with a pre-built `ModeToggle` component.
- Run: `npx shadcn@latest add dropdown-menu`.
- Then create `src/components/mode-toggle.tsx` using `DropdownMenu` + `useTheme`. Refer to the [shadcn/ui dark mode docs](https://ui.shadcn.com/docs/dark-mode/next).
- shadcn/ui's default CSS variables already include `--background`, `--foreground`, etc., that flip automatically when the `dark` class is present — no extra config needed.

### 7. Apply dark mode classes in your UI
- Use Tailwind's `dark:` prefix for dark-mode-specific styles:
  ```tsx
  <div className="bg-white text-black dark:bg-gray-900 dark:text-white">
    Content
  </div>
  ```
- For CSS variables (shadcn/ui style), define them in `:root` and `.dark` in your global CSS:
  ```css
  :root { --bg: #ffffff; --fg: #000000; }
  .dark { --bg: #0f0f0f; --fg: #ffffff; }
  ```

### 8. Verify
- Start the dev server: `npm run dev`.
- Open the app, click the toggle — the page should switch between light and dark.
- Reload the page — the chosen theme should persist (stored in `localStorage` as `theme`).
- Set your OS to dark mode and set theme to `system` — the page should follow your OS preference.
- Check DevTools: the `<html>` element should have `class="dark"` in dark mode.

### Common errors & fixes
- **Flash of wrong theme on load (FOUC)** — You are missing `suppressHydrationWarning` on `<html>` or `disableTransitionOnChange` on `ThemeProvider`. Add both.
- **`useTheme` must be inside ThemeProvider** — `ThemeProvider` is missing from the root layout. Add it wrapping `{children}` in `layout.tsx`.
- **Hydration mismatch: `className` did not match** — You are rendering the theme-dependent UI before `mounted` is `true`. Add the `mounted` guard to any component that renders differently per theme.
- **Dark classes not applying** — Check `darkMode: 'class'` is set in `tailwind.config.ts`. Verify `attribute="class"` is set on `ThemeProvider`.
- **Theme not persisting after refresh** — `localStorage` is not available in SSR. This is expected; next-themes handles it automatically once the client hydrates.
- **`resolvedTheme` vs `theme`** — When `theme` is `'system'`, it returns `'system'`, not the actual resolved value. Use `resolvedTheme` to get `'light'` or `'dark'` when displaying the current icon.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT render theme-dependent UI without the `mounted` guard — you will get hydration errors.
- Do NOT use `darkMode: 'media'` in Tailwind if you want a user toggle — media-mode cannot be overridden programmatically.
- Do NOT add `ThemeProvider` inside a page or individual component — it must wrap the entire app in the root layout.
- Do NOT read `localStorage` directly to get the theme — use `useTheme()` which handles SSR, hydration, and the system preference automatically.
- Do NOT place `'use client'` on `layout.tsx` to use `ThemeProvider` — `ThemeProvider` itself is already a Client Component; the layout can stay a Server Component.
- Do NOT forget `suppressHydrationWarning` on `<html>` — without it, React will log false-positive hydration warnings every time the theme is applied.
